This particular corner of the digital archives, this rather specific [category](/Help:Category), is dedicated to the rather mundane, yet utterly essential, phenomenon of [redirects](/Wikipedia:Redirect) that arise from [moved (or, as the less dramatic among us might say, renamed)](/Wikipedia:Move) titles. It's a testament to the ever-shifting landscape of information, where even the names of things are not immune to change. These entries exist as echoes of what once was, ensuring that the path to knowledge, however convoluted, remains unbroken.

Should you find yourself compelled to contribute to this intricate system, the protocol is, naturally, quite precise. To properly usher a redirect into this category's embrace, you are instructed to place the somewhat nested `{{[Rcat shell](/Template:Rcat_shell)}|{{[R from move](/Template:R_from_move)}}}` template. This incantation must be inscribed on the *second* new line – not the first, mind you, that would imply a lack of proper reverence for structure – immediately following the `#REDIRECT [[Target page name]]` directive. A deliberate skip of a line is paramount. Failure to adhere to such seemingly arbitrary spacing could, theoretically, cause the very fabric of Wikipedia's internal consistency to fray. For those seeking further enlightenment on the intricacies of this process, the provided links offer a deeper dive into the arcane arts.

A word of caution, however, for the overzealous: one must *never* [substitute](/Wikipedia:Substitution) these redirect template(s). They are designed to be dynamic, living entities, not to be flattened into static code. Nor, for that matter, should they be imposed upon [soft redirects](/Wikipedia:Soft_redirect); those delicate constructs serve a different, equally vital, purpose and should not be contaminated by misapplied enthusiasm.

For the truly dedicated, a more comprehensive exploration of the various [redirect templates](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Redirect_pages) awaits, along with the meticulously crafted [redirect style guide](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Redirect/Style_guide). It's all there, for those who find joy in the granular mechanics of digital organization.

### Nature and Function of This Category

This entire edifice, this collection of digital breadcrumbs, is fundamentally a [maintenance](/Wikipedia:Maintenance) [category](/Help:Category). Its existence is not to enrich the encyclopedic content itself, but rather to facilitate the ceaseless, often thankless, [maintenance of the Wikipedia project](/Wikipedia:Categorization). It is, in essence, the behind-the-scenes machinery, the filing cabinet of the grand library. Consequently, it is not considered part of the public-facing encyclopedia proper. Instead, it primarily contains [non-article pages](/Wikipedia:What_is_an_article%3F) or, when it does touch upon actual articles, it groups them not by their subject matter – the historical significance of a battle, the biological classification of a rare species – but by their administrative *status*. It's a practical, rather than pedagogical, classification system.

More specifically, this is classified as a [tracking category](/Category:Tracking_categories). Its primary directive is not to categorize knowledge for the casual browser, but to systematically build and maintain a comprehensive list of pages. The list itself is the artifact of value here, a ledger of digital shifts. It does not integrate into the [encyclopedia's main categorization scheme](/Wikipedia:Categorization) that organizes information by topic. Instead, its utility lies in its capacity to monitor and organize the internal workings of the platform.

A rather curious feature of these categories is that they are [hidden](/Wikipedia:Categorization) by default on their individual [member pages](/Category:Hidden_categories). This means that only those with a specific, almost voyeuristic, interest in the underlying structure will ever see them. To reveal these hidden layers, a user must actively adjust their [user preference](/Special:Preferences) (specifically under "Appearance," by selecting "Show hidden categories"). It's a small concession to those who prefer to keep the clutter of operational details out of sight, leaving the clean facade of the encyclopedia intact.

These categories serve a dual purpose:
*   They are instrumental in tracking, building, and organizing lists of pages that require "attention en masse." This might include pages employing deprecated syntax, or those simply needing a human eye at someone's earliest convenience. Think of it as a digital to-do list for the conscientious editor.
*   Furthermore, they excel at aggregating members from various lists or sub-categories into a larger, more efficient master list. This aggregation is often further refined by specific classifications, allowing for a more nuanced approach to project management and oversight.

### The Purpose of Redirects from Moves

The fundamental reason for the existence of these redirects is to prevent the digital equivalent of a broken promise: to [avoid breaking links](/Wikipedia:RCAT). Whether these links are internal, connecting one Wikipedia article to another, or external, originating from websites beyond Wikipedia's direct control, their integrity is paramount. When an article's title changes, the old title doesn't simply vanish into the ether; it becomes a redirect, a signpost pointing to its new location. This ensures that any previous references, any bookmarks, any citations, continue to lead to the correct destination, preserving the interconnected web of information.

The `{{[R from move](/Template:R_from_move)}}` template, which is the mechanism used to tag these redirects and populate this specific category, is often added automatically. This occurs during the very act of a page move or rename, a small mercy in the otherwise meticulous process. However, the system is not infallible. Older redirects, those created before such automation was fully implemented or refined, may still linger, untagged and unclassified. These stragglers require manual intervention, a testament to the ongoing human effort required to maintain even the most sophisticated automated systems.

